column62: Dropped; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AFTER THE DRIVER COMPLETED A PROPER PRE TRIP INSPECTION HE DEPARTED THE TERMINAL YARD AND DROVE 1.3 MILES TO THE LOADING POINT.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN LOADED WITH 8800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  AFTER LOADING THE TRAILER THE DRIVER DEPARTED THE LOADING POINT AND DROVE ANOTHER 1.8 MILES TO THE POINT WHEN THE KING PIN OF THE TRAILER BECAME DISENGAGED FROM THE FIFTH WHEEL OF THE TRACTOR.  AFTER THE KING PIN BECAME DISENGAGED FROM THE FIFTH WHEEL THE TRAILER SLID OFF THE BACK OF THE TRACTOR AND THE DOLLIES OF THE TRAILER IMPACTED THE PAVEMENT, COLLAPSED AND THE TRAILER NOSE THEN RESTED ON THE PAVEMENT.  WHEN THE DOLLIES COLLAPSED ONE OF THE DOLLY SUPPORT BRACES PENETRATED #2 COMPARTMENT SPILLING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THAT COMPARTMENT.  THE OTHER COMPARTMENTS RETAINED THE PRODUCT WHICH WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER 306AL CARGO TANK.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT RAN TO THE CURB SIDE OF THE ROAD AND DIRECTLY INTO A STORM DRAIN WHICH LED DIRECTLY TO THE ALLEGHENY RIVER. IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN BY THE LOCAL FIRE AND POLICE TO SECURE THE AREA.  UNITED REFINING COMPANY PROVIDED FOAM TO PLACE ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  A BOOM WAS PLACED IN THE RIVER BELOW THE STORM DRAIN AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR VACUUMED THE PRODUCT FROM THE WATER.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE A ONE BLOCK AREA SURROUNDING THE SCENE WAS EVACUATED FROM ABOUT 0830 UNTIL 1330 THAT DAY.  AT ABOUT 1500 THAT DAY LOCAL DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT PERSONNEL WERE SATISFIED THAT THE AREA WAS FREE OF CONTAMINATION AND REQUESTED THAT THE BOOM BE PULLED.  SINCE THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONFINED TO THE BLACKTOP AREA AND STORM SEWER NO EXCAVATION OF EARTH WAS REQUIRED.  ON 10-14-92 THE US DOT INVESTIGATORS, PA PUC AND LOCAL POLICE CONDUCTED AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE WHICH AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT IS CONTINUING.  AT THE PRESENT TIME ALL COUPLING PROCEDURES ARE BEING REVIEWED AND THE MANUFACTURER IS BEING CONSULTED.  AFTER COMPLETION OF THIS RE-EVALUATION ALL EMPLOYEES WILL BE RETRAINED IN COUPLING PROCEDURES.  THIS INVESTIGATION REMAINS OPEN AS OF 10-16-92.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON OCTOBER 9, 1992 AT LOS ANGELES INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT, TWA FLIGHT 90/07 OCTOBER, HONOLULU TO LOS ANGELES, OUR CARGO SERVICES SUPERVISOR RECEIVED A CALL (AT APPROXIMATELY 0700) FROM OUR CARGO RAMPSERVICE PERSON, REQUESTING THAT THE SUPERVISOR MEET HIM OUTSIDE OUR CARGO TERMINAL TO INSPECT A SHIPMENT. UPON INSPECTION, 3 OF 4 CARTONS WERE WELL SOAKED AND THERE WERE PUDDLES OF LIQUID IN THE CARGO WAGON.  ALSO, THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR FROM THE SHIPMENT.  WE HAD TWO MECHANICS INSPECT THE SHIPMENT WITH THE SUPERVISOR AND THEY CONCURRED THAT THE LIQUID APPEARED TO BE BATTERY ACID. THE GROUND OPERATIONS MANAGER WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND HE WITH A MAINTENANCE FOREMAN INSPECTED THE AIRCRAFT.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO HAVE A PLANE CHANGE TO AIRCRFT.  THE DECISION WA SMADE TO HAVE A PLANE CHANGE TO AIRCRAFT 21020 FOR THE INTENDED DEPARTURE OF THIS AIRCRAFT.  THIS DECISION WAS MADE BASED ON THE FACT THAT THE BATTERIES HAD LEAKED FLUID ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE BULK SECTION.  THIS PLANE CHANGE ALLOWED TWA TIME FOR CLEANING OF THE AFFECTED AREA. THE GROUND OPERATIONS MANAGER CONTACTED THE LOS ANGELES CAFSO OFFICE AND THEY ADVISED THAT THEY WOUL DBE SENDING THEIR PERSONNEL TO OUR CARGO FACILITY. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY TWA PERSONNEL, IT REVEALED THAT 1-CARTON AND 3-CRATES HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELS.  UPON CLOSRE SCRUTINY OF THE CARTON AND CRATES, YOU COULD BARELY MAKE OUT SOME ENGLISH WORKDS INDICATING A JAPANESE BATTERY COMPANY.  THERE WERE ALSO SOME SMALL (APPROXIMATELY 2 INCHES0 FADED RED ARROWS ON THE CARTONS (CONTAINING THE BATTERIES) WHICH WERE PARTIALLY OBSCURED BY THE WOOD CRATING.

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD JUST LEFT A TRUCK STOP WHEN HE WAS HAILED BY A DEPUTY SHERIFF AND ADVISED THAT SOMETHING WAS COMING OFF THE BACK OF ONE OF THE MUDFLAPS ON THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER PULLED OVER AT THE FIRST OPPORTUNITY. THE DEPUTY PULLED OVER ALSO AND ADVISED THAT HE HAD REPORTED THE MATTER TO THE CHP AND WOUL DNOT LET OUR DRIVER ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS.  THE CHP NOTIFIED OUR NEAREST TERMINAL AND PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  WHEN THEY ARRIVE THEY WERE ALLOWED TO INSPECT THE TANK AND FOUND THAT THE REAR MOST CLEANOUT CAP ON TOP FHTE TRAILER WAS LEAKING A LITTLE PRODUCT.  THE CAP WAS REPLACED AND THE RESIDUE CLEANED FROM THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER WAS THEN ALLOWED TO PROCEED.

THE PRODUCT BACKED UP INTO HIS HOSES.  WHEN HE DISCONNECTED ONE OF HIS DROP HOSES, APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED OUT ONTO THE LOT.  OUR CLEANUP CONTACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  THE DELAWARE DER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

OUR SPILL CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CLEAN THE SPILL AND REPLACED GRAVEL.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: AT RECEIVER, DRIVER NOTICED ALL THE BOXES HAD DAMP AREAS ON THEM.  UPON INSPECTION, DRIVER FOUND THAT THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS INSIDE THE BOXES HAD CRACKED OPEN AROUND THE HANDLE JOINT.  SHIPPER HIRED A CREW TOCOME OUT AND REPACKAGE ENTIRE LOAD INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS.  LOAD WAS THEN RECONSIGNED TRO A DIFFERENT RECEIVER DUE TO BEING REFUSED.  ALL MATERIAL OFF-LOADED AT RECEIVER AND TRAILER STEAM-CLEANED

DRUM RECEIVER AT CMP 375 IN A DAMAGED CONDITION.  BOTTOM OF DRUMW AS CREASED, AND AS A RESULT A HAIRLINE CRACK ALLOWED THE EXTRACT TO LEAK ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURN TO SHIPPER.

THE CAMEO TRUCK STOP TANKS ARE ALL MANIFOLDED TOGETHER.  OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER OPENED A VALVE TO THE WRONG TANK AND BEGAN PUMPING OFF HIS CARGO. THE TANK OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING INTO WOULD NOT HOLD THE ENTIRE LOAD SO THE STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFILLED.  SPILLED FUEL CAME OUT VENT PIPES AND ENTERRED THE CONTAINMENT AREA AROUND THE TANK FARM. WE PUMPED AS MUCH FUEL AS POSSIBLE FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA - APPROXIMAELY 450 GALLONS AND DISPOSED OF IT AT AN APPROVED FACILITY.  WE THEN REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL THAT LINED THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND PLACEDIT ONA SHEET OF VISQUEEN WHERE IT WILL BE LAND FARMED AND DRIED. CLEAN GRAVEL WAS PLACED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. OUR DRIVER WAS PLACED ON PROBATION FOR A 6 MONTH PERIOD OF TIME FOR FAILURE TO PROPERLY CHECK TANKS BEING FILLED AT THE TANK FARM.  HE WAS ALSO GIVEN FURTHER INSTRUCTION FROM THE CAMEO FACILITY ABOUT THEIR MANIFOLDING SYSTEM.

SPILLED PRODUCT AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE REMOVED.  REMAINDER OF PRODUCT TRANSLOADED FROM DAMAGED CAR AND RETURNED TO STERLING CHEMICALS.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: OUR TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ENROUTE TO THE RECEIVER.  CLEAN HARBOR FRO NATICK, MA, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND DISCOVERED 4 DRUMS WITH DEFECTIVE SEALS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE SPILLAGE FROM THESE DRUMS WAS ABSORBED AND THE DRUMS RESEALED.  THE RECEIVER, CLEANR HARBOR, SENT A TRAILER TO THE SCENE AND ALL CARGO WAS REMOVED FRO DELIVERY.  OUR TRAILER WAS CLEANED THOROUGHLY AND ALL RESIDUE REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL BY CLEAN HARBOR.

THE LOADED HAD UNLOADED INTO TOTES, THE PRODUCT HOSE WAS HOOKED TO A LINE THAT WENT THROUGH THE WALL.  WHEN THE TRAILER WENT EMPTY THE PRE FINISH EMPLOYEE DRAINED THE PRESSURE OFF OF THELINE AND SHUT THEIR VALVE OFF. CENTRAL DRIVER HAD CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE CENTRAL TANK AND HAD SLOWLY UNHOOKED THE CENTRAL HOSE BY UNHOOKING ONE EAR AT A TIME AND WIGGLED THE HOSE AND THERE WAS NO PRESSURE ON THE HOSE.  CENTRAL DRIVER STEPPED BACK ABOUT ONE FOOT WHEN PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF THE HOSE.

FORKLIFT BLADES PUNCTURED HOLE IN A 55 GALLON DRUM OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID. ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF THIS MATERIAL WAS LOST FROM THIS ACCIDENT.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP OFF THE DOCK WITH FLOOR DRY.  IT WAS THEN PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: SHIPMENT ARRIVE CHARLOTTE CC WITH 1 CARTON TURNED ON ITS SIDE CAUSING CONTENTS TO LEAK.  CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND FREIGHT SENT ON TO DESTINATION. ALL ASSOCIATED DEBRIS BEING HELD AT CHR CC FOR DISPOSAL.

AFTER DELIVERING INTERMODAL CONTAINER ITLU 528600 TO CNW-GLOBAL II FACILITY, DRIVER REPORTED FINDING WET SPOT ON CHASSIS.  SMELL CONFIRMED TO PROBABILITY OF A RELEASE.  CONTRACTOR (OH MATERIALS) WAS CALLED TO EXAMINE TO LOAD.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT PRODUCT WAS ON TOP OF SEVENS DRUM (OF 76 IN THE CONTAINER0 WITH SOME PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR. IT IS BELIEVED THAT UNUSUALLY MILD TEMPERATURES CAUSED EXPANSION IN DRUMS RESULTING IN SEEPAGE THROUGH BUNG SEALS.  (LOAD HAD ORIGINATED IN ENGLAND, COMNG THROUGH THE PORT OF MONTREAL.  IT MOVED TO CHICAGO AREA VIA RAIL (CP-SOO) WHERE IT WAS DELIVERED VIA HIGHWAY TO CNW FOR RAIL MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.)  LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED.  OTHER DRUMS WERE DECONTAMINATED AS REQUIRED AND RELEASED.  FLOORING OF CONTAINER WAS REMOVED AS NECESSARY AND WILL BE INCINERATED. CONTAINER WAS NOT PLACARDED.  A NUMBER OF POISON LABELS WERE APPLIED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINER.

column168: #1 WAS APPROACHING A LEFT HAND TURN AND HAD SLOWED TO MAKE THE TURN.  THE TRAILER SUDDENLY DIPPED TO THE LEFT SEVERLY JUST BEFORE UNIT WENT INTO THE LEFT HAND TURN.  AS THE DRIVER WAS ENTERING THE LEFT HAND TURN THE TRAILER LEANED TOO FAR TO THE RIGHT AND THE ENTIRE UNIT TIPPED OVER TO THE RIGHT. THE ENTIRE UNIT TIPPED OVER LANDING ON IT'S TOP. IT IS BELIEVED THAT A LEFT FRONT TRAILER SPRING BROKE JUST AS UNIT WAS ENTERING THE LEFT HAND TURN. THERE IS NO SPRING ON THE LEFT FRONT POSITION AND THERE ONE WHEN THE UNIT WAS PRE-TRIP INSPECTED APPROXIMATELY 35 MINITES BEFORE THE INCIDENT. THE CARGO LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER FROM THE WEEP HOLES BETWEEN THE BULK HEADS BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS 2 THRU 5. THE BULK HEADS HAD BROKEN LOOSE DURING THE INCIDENT.  THE LOAD CONSISTED OF 8500 GALS OF PRODUCT AND ALL BUT 3000 GALS WERE SAVE DURING CLEAN UP.

column168: AT 0820 MDT ON OCTOBER 16, 1992, TRAIN 01-196-14 DERAILED THE 10TH THROUGH 16TH CARS AT MP 341.24 ON THE DENVER DIVISION 8TH SUBDIVISION NEAR LUCERNE, WYOMING.  FOUR OF THE DERAILED CARS WERE TANK CARS CARRYING METHYL ALCOHOL.  TANK CAR AGCX 10136 HAD A HOLE TORN IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK WHERE A BRAKE RIGGING BRACKET WAS WELDED TO THE TANK SHELL AND APPROXIMATELY 40-50 PERCENT OF THE LADING WAS RELEASED.  TANK CAR AGCF 10069 SUSTAINED A 6-7 FOOT RIP IN THE TANK HEAD AND 100 PERCENT OF THE LADING WAS RELEASED.  TANK CAR NCTX 29665 SUSTAINED ABOUT A 6 FOOT DENT IN THE TANK SIDE AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF LADING.  TANK CAR AGCF 10024 REMAINED ALMOST UPRIGHT WITH ONE END OF THE TANK ABOUT 30 DEGREES LOWER THAN THE OTHER END AND THERE WAS LEAKAGE AT THE TOP LOADING/UNLOADING FITTINGS AT A RATE OF ABOUT 5 GALLONS A MINUTE.

column168: A 345 GALLON PORTABLE TANK CONTAINING A STYRENE MONOMER WASTE WAS EN ROUTE FROM GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY'CHEMICAL DIVISION IN OTTAWA, IL TO CLEAN HARBORS OFBRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA WHEN THE DRIVER OBSERVED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THEREAR OF THE CAN TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED HIS VEHICLE, VISUALLY CONFIRMED THAT MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOOR AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR AS TO HIS LOCATION AND SITUATIO. THE DISPATCHER THEN INITIATED NOTIFICATION PROCEDURES TO INFORM STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES OF THE RELEASE. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS ALSO DISPATCHED FORM CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. SERVICE CENTER AT THIS TIME. AFTER PLACING THE CALL TO DISPATCH, THE DRIVER CONSTRUCTED A DIKE WITH EQUIPMENT CARRIED IN THE TRAILERS "SPILL KIT". THIS CONTAINED THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE PAVED ROADWAY AND PREVENTED ANY SOIL CONTAMINATION FROM OCCURRING. WHILE PERFORMING THIS OPERATION, THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE ALONG WITH LOCAL FIRE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE GROUPS. THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES TOOK CONTROL OF THE AREA AN WERE PROVIDED WITH COPIES OF ALL SHIPPING DOCUMENTS. AT THIS POINT, THE LOCAL AGENCIES AT THE SCENE PROCEEDED TO ENTER THE VEHICLE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. ONCE RELEASED AND CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER (APPROXIMATELY 245 GALLONS) BE ABSORBED WITH SPEEDY DRY MAKING IT SAFE TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO AN ALTERNATE LOCATION FOR DECONTAMINATION AND CLEAN-UP. THE VEHICLE WAS THEN SEALED AND ESCORTED TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. WHERE THE CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION WAS COMPLETED. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE BY CLEAN HARBORS CONTAINERIZED ALL THE DEBRIS RESULTING FROM THE RELEASE (APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS OF STYRENE) AND CLEANED THE AREA TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE ILLINOIS EPA REPRESENTATIVE ON SITE. ALL DEBRIS RESULTING FROM THE RELEASE WAS THEN SHIPPED TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOTTOM VALVE CAP ON THE PORTABLE TANK IN QUESTION WAS NOT SUFFICIENTLY TIGHTENED. BOTH THE DRIVER AND THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE SHIPPER HAVE STATED THAT THE VALVE WAS CHECKED BY HAND TO INSURE THAT THE CAP WAS IN PLACE PRIOR TO SHIPMENT. IT IS EVIDENT, HOWEVER, THAT IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ALL TANK VALVES MUST BE TIGHTENED WITH A PIPE WRENCH PRIOR TO DEPARTURE TO INSURE THAT ALL VALVES ARE SUFFICIENTLY CLOSED. THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT (REPORT #141814).

ABOUT TWO HOURS AFTER DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE DRIVER PULLED OFF THE ROAD FOR A ROUTINE INSPECTION. AT THAT TIME THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE NO.4 COMPARTMENT ON THE CURB SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK. THE DRIVER SET A 5 GALLON PAIL UNDER THE DRIP FOR CONTAINMENT, THEN CALLED ME AT HOME. I INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO SET OUT HIS WARNING REFLECTORS, KEEP PEOPLE AWAY FROM THE SCENE, AND CONTINUE WITH THE CURRENT CONTAINMENT UNTIL ANOTHER TANK ARRIVED TO PUMP OFF THE LEAKING COMPARTMENT. AN EMPTY CARGO TANK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND THE TRANSFER WAS MADE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. DURING THE FOUR AND A HALF HOUR WAITING FOR THE SECOND TANKER TO ARRIVE AND TRANSFER, ONLY 2 1/2 GALLONS DRIPPED INTO THE CONTAINMENT PAIL. THAT 2 1/2 GALLONS WAS THEN POURED INTO THE SECOND CARGO TANK, ELIMINATING ANY WASTE DISPOSAL. THIS WOULD ALSO INDICATE THAT ONLY A VERY SMALL AMOUNT COULD HAVE BEEN LOST IN THE 2 HOUR PERIOD BETWEEN THE LOADING OF THE TANKER AND THE DISCOVERY OF THE LEAK. THE FOLLOWING DAY THE CARGO TANK WAS SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR INSPECTION, REPAIR, PRESSURE TESTING, AND PLACED BACK IN SERVICE ON OCT. 11, 1992. A SMALL CRACK WAS FOUND WHERE THE THERMO-WELL WAS ATTACHED TO THE CARGO TANK.

WEIGHT IS APPROXIMATELY 10LBS PER GALLON. PAILCAPACITY OF 2.64 GALLONS PRODUCES A GROSS WEIGHT (PAIL PLUS LIQUID) OF ROUGHLY25LBS. THIS EQUATES TO 500 LBS PER ROW. IT WAS THE BOTTOM ROWS ON THE SKIDS WHICH HAD THE MANY BENT, COLLAPSED,BUCKLED AND CRACKED (FRACTURED) PAILS. IT WAS FOUND THAT A TOTAL OF 120 PAILSSUSTAINED DAMAGE. THIS LISTED BELOW: A). 47 BENT ON BOTTOMS. B).23 BENT,CREASED AND/OR BUCKLED ON SIDES. C). 30 BENT ON TOP AREAS (CAUSED BY BANDINGAND/OR LACK OF PROTECTIVE ANGLEBOARD). column168: AT ABOUT 11:00 AM ON OCTOBER 22,1992 A LAROCHE DRIVER HAD JUST COMPLETED DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA INTO A SPECTRA PHYSICS STORAGE TANK.  AS THE LAROCHE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE AMMONIA TRANSFER PUMP, THE PUMP SHAFT FAILED AND AMMONIA PRODUCT BEGAN DISCHARGING THROUGH A 1/8" WEEP HOLE AND FROM AROUND THE SHAFT SEAL.  THE FISHER INTERNAL VALVE ALSO FAILED TO SEAT PROPERLY.  LAROCHE EFFORTS, AS WELL AS THE EFFORTS OF EMERGENCY RESPONDERS FAILED TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL SAFETY VALVE.  ABOUT 700 LBS OF AMMONIA WAS DISCHARGED TO THE ENVIRONMENT OVER 8 HOURS.

column168: SORT SUPERVISOR TONY BUTCHER REPORTED A SPILL IN THE CANADIAN CAGE ARE OF BUILDING B OF OUR SORT FACILITY. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS A CLEAR LIQUID, ODOR OF ALCOHOL, 2 EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT. CERT 11 HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, FRAN VANCE AND CERT 10 P/T SPILL TECH, ADDIE CAMPTON, ARRIVED ON SCENE. WE FOUND A YELLOW C CONTAINER WITH 5 GREEN RUBBERMAID STORAGE CONTAINERS, SEALED WITH CLEAR PACKAGING TAPE. THESE CONTAINERS WERE LOADED ON TOP APPROX. 10 PLASTIC BAGS OF EXPRESS ENVELOPES. THE CLEAR LIQUID WAS TESTED, NO PH READING, SLIGHT ODOR OF ALCOHOL. THE CONTAINERS WERE UNLOADED, ONE OF THE CONTAINERS PACKAGED AS FOLLOWS, SMALL NASCO WHIRL-PAKS INSIDE AN ADDITIONAL NASCO WHIRL-PAK EACH WHIRL-PAK SEALED WITH PINCH TYPE CLOSURES. THESE WERE PACKED IN A LARGE CLEAR PACKAGING TAPE. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM THE PINCH TYPE CLOSURES NOT MAKING AN ADEQUATE SEAL TO CONTAIN THE FLUID INSIDE. THERE WAS AN INTERNATIONAL BILL OF LANDING AND A SHIPMENT INVOICE ATTACHED TO ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WHICH STATED THE CONTENTS WERE "SEDIMENT SAMPLES". THE INVOICE STATED "SEDIMENT SAMPLES IN ETHANOL, THE ETHANOL HAD BEEN MARKED THROUGH AND WATER PRINTED UNDER THE MARKED THROUGH ETHANOL, THERE WAS A SIGNATURE AT THE CORRECTION. DUE TO THE CONFLICT OF THE LIQUID THE SEDIMENT SAMPLES WERE PACKAGED IN, THE ODOR AND THE EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT, THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER. ALL OF THE EXPRESS MAIL WAS REPACKAGED INTO NEW PLASTIC BAGS, THE CONTAINERS OF SEDIMENT SAMPLES WERE PLACED INTO PLASTIC BAGS AND TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT. THE SHIPPER SENT A LETTER STATING THE SHIPMENT WAS MADE UP OF APPROX. 200 LAKE SEDIMENT SAMPLES (MUD AND BENTHIC INVERTEBRATES). THESE SAMPLES WERE PRESERVED IN 70% ETHANOL. UPON DETERMINING THAT THEY DECIDED TO SHIP THE SAMPLES WITHOUT PRESERVATIVE AND REPRESERVE IMMEDIATELY UPON ARRIVAL AT THEIR DESTINATION. THE SHIPPER ALSO STATED THAT THE ETHANOL WAS REMOVED BY DECANTING THE SAMPLES AND TRANSFERRING THE SEDIMENT TO WHIRLPACK  BAGS BY RINSING THE ORIGINAL SEDIMENT OUT OF THE CONTAINERS WITH WATER, THUS DILUTING ANY REMAINING ETHANOL TO ONLY TRACE AMOUNTS. DUE TO THE ODOR BEING STRONGER THAN A TRACE, A FIELD TEST FOR FLAMMABILITY WAS DONE. A RANDOM SAMPLE WAS TAKEN FROM EACH OF THE 5 CONTAINERS, A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE LIQUID TESTED AND EACH OF THE SAMPLES BURNED. THE ETHANOL HAD NOT BEEN REMOVED FROM THE SAMPLES. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THESE FINDINGS AND A SECOND MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR ETHANOL WAS RECEIVED. THERE WERE APPROX. 280 SEDIMENT SAMPLES FROM THE 5 CONTAINERS ALL WITH ETHANOL. TOTAL AMOUNT OF ETHANOL ESTIMATED TO BE 33.6 LITERS. THE GREEN RUBBERMAID STORAGE CONTAINERS ARE APPROX. 24" X 10" X 12" IN SIZE. FROM THE MSDS, THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME IS FOUND TO BE ETHANOL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1170. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT IT;S CONTENTS WERE REGUALTED AS A HAZA

WHILE SWITCHING TANK CAR RTMX 2649 TRAIN CREW NOTED PRODUCT SPLASHING FROM TOP OF CAR. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. CARRIER MECHANICAL PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND FOUND THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT UNDER MOVEMENT. BOLTS TIGHTENED AND CAR SAFE FOR MOVEMENT. ONE CREW MEMBER WAS SPLASHED BY THE PRODUCT AND TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL CLINIC FOR EXAMINATION. EXAMINATION REVEALED NO INJURY AND NO FURTHER MEDICAL ATTENTION OR LOST TIME INCURRED. CONTACTED MR. CLIFF MCLAIN, TRAFFIC MANAGER, GULF STATES STEEL AND ADVISED HIM OF THIS PROBLEM. HE STATED HE WOULD HANDLE FOR CORRECTIONS.

ON OCTOBER 1, 92, DRIVER DONALD PARKS AND HELPER GREGORY HASKE LOADED "SULFURIC ACID" CORROSIVE MATERIAL UN1830 FROM A RAIL TANK CAR AT NORTH F. STREET, INTO OUR CARGO TANK.  AFTER COMPLETING THE LOADING PROCESS, MR. PRAKS AND MR. HASKE DISCONNECTED AIR HOSE AND PRODUCT HOSE FROM TANK CAR AND CARGO TANK, SECURED RAIL SIDING AND TANK CAR,  DRIVER THEN LEFT SIDING TO DELIVER THE LOAD TO COZINCO AT 100 N. LEAD STREET, SALIDA.  WE HAVE DETERMINED THAT OUR DRIVER DONALD PARKS DID NOT CLOSE THE AIR VALVE COMPLETELY ON THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK, AND EACH TIME THE DRIVER STOPPED OR SLOWED DOWN, THEN ACCELERATED, THE PRODUCT WOULD SURGE TOWARD THE REAR AND FORCE A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT OUT OF THE ONE INCH AIR PIPE.  WE BELEIVE FOUR TO FIVE GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID SPRAYED ON THE STREET AND ON THREE PARKED VEHICLES.  A CITY EMPLOYEE WITNESSED THE INCIDENT AND CALLED POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS.  THE POLICE DEPARTMENT STOPPED TRAFFIC WHILE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT NEUTRALIZED AND DELUTED THE ACID ON THE STREET AND ON THE PARKED VEHICLES.  WE HAVE INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS AND HELPERS TO CHECK AND RECHECK EACH OTHERS WORK, ESPECIALLY ON THE PIPING AND VALVES ON BOTH CARGO TANKS AND TANK CARS.  WE HAVE ALSO INSTRUCTED OUR SALIDA TERMINAL MANAGER TO ACOMPANY OUR DRIVERS PERIODICALLY TO HELP PREVENT DRIVERS AND HELPERS FROM TAKNG SHORT CUTS WHILE LOADING AND UNLOADING.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.C. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY ITS DISPATCHER THAT IT WAS NOTED APLU 78883 WAS LEAKING A DARK LIQUID. SSA/HM COOPER RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE SHRINK WRAPPED IN SETS OF THREE AND SET ON PALLETS.   THERE WERE ALSO A TOTAL OF 18 DRUMS IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, SHRINK WRAPPED, AND SET ON PALLETS.  THESE WERE SET ON THE TOP OF THE FIRST LAYER OF DRUMS.  DRUMS WERE NOT PROPERY BLOCKED AND BRACED WHICH ALLOWED THE DRUMS TO DROP FROM THE PALLETS.  THE TOP ROLLING HOOPS ON TWO DRUMS RUBBED TOGETHER AND FATIGUED THE METAL ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  ALL OTHER DRUMS AHD SIMILAR WEAR BUT WERE ALL INTACT.  CONTENTS WERE OFF LOADED, INSPECTED AND PLACED BACK INTO CONTAINER AFTER CLEANING WAS COMPLETED.  THE TWO DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS AND PLACED BACK IN THE CONTAINER.  THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED PRIOR TO BEING RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. CHEMTREC AND CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

ON THURSDAY OCTOBER 15, 1992 ASHLAND CHEMICAL INC., ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES SOUTH BEND, INDIANA WAS RETURNING A DRUM OF REJECTED CUSTOMER WASTE (DUE TO COLOR) TO THE ORIGINAL GENERATOR OF THE MATERIAL IN CHICAGO.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DRIVER LEFT THE SOUTH BEND INDIANA FACILITY AT 3:30 A.M. ON THURSDAY MORNING IN THE RAIN WITH JUST THIS ONE DRUM IN THE BACK OF THIS TRUCK (LOAD BARS AROUND EACH SIDE OF DRUM).  HE ARRIVED IN THE RAIN AT THE ASHLAND CHEMICAL INC., WILLOW SPRINGS FACILITY (TO PICK UP WASTE FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO SOUTH BEND BEFORE RETURNING DRUM TO CUSTOMER0 AND DISCOVERED AFTER BACKING INTO DICK AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 THAT THE DRUM CART SLID IN THE TRUCK TO THE BACK AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM ABOUT 5" - 6" ABOVE THE BOTTOM.  STEPS HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO PREVENT THIS REOCCURANCE, DRUMS CARTS WILL BE SECURED ON ALL VEHICLES.  PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN TO CONTAIN AND I WAS NOTIFIED AT 7:30 A.M.  INVESTIGATIONS THEN WERE DONE ON SITE IMMEDIATELY TO SEE IF IT HAD LEAKED AT THE WILLOW SPRINGS FACILITY, BUT DUE TO THE CONSTANT RAIL NOTHING COUL BE SEEN OR NO ODOR WAS DETECTED. ALL THE APPLICABLE AGENCIES PLUS THE GENERATOR WERE CONTACTED PER OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES IN OUR ASHLAND CHEMICAL INC. SOUTH BEND, INDIANA.  THE DRUM WAS THEN OVERPACKED AT ASHLAND CHEMICAL INC. WILLOW SPRINGS AND LABELED.  THE BACK OF THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED WITH WIPED AND THESE WIPED ALONG WITH SOME DEBRIS ON THE GROUND WERE THEN PUT INTO A DRUM WAS FUTURE DISPOSAL. THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR TSDF FACILITY IN SOUTH BEND FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DRUM OF WIPES AN DEBRIS AT THE WILLOW SPRINGS FACILITY WILL BE PROFILED AND SAMPLED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO A CONVENIENCE STORE'S UST.  THE UST WAS EQUIPPED WITH AN OPW FUELING COMPONENTS GROUP (CINCINNATI, OHIO) TYPE OPW61-SO OVERFILL PREVENTION ALVE.  AS OUR DRIVER WAS JUST ABOUT UNLOADED, THE GAS IN THE UST ACTIVATED THE OPW VALVE WHICH SLAMMED SHUT WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO BLOW OUR DELIVERY HOSE OFF THE UST.  THIS ALLOWED ABOUT 15 GALLONS OF GAS THAT WAS STILL IN THE DELIVERY HOSE TO LEAK ONTO THE BLACKTOP.  THE GAS WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH PADS AND CLAY ABSORBENTS.  AN INSPECTION OF OUR FITTINGS AS WELL AS THE OP VALVE SHOWED NO DEFECT IN EITHER.  NO EXPLANATION HAS BEEN FOUND AS TO WHY THE OPW VALVE SHUT WITH SUCH FORCE.  A REVIEW OF MY FILES FINDS THAT THIS TYPE OF PROBLEMS HAS OCCURRED ONCE BEFORE AT ANOTHER LOCATION EQUIPPED WITH THE SAME TYPE VALVE.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE 39208673 TO THIS INCIDENT.

UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX,  I FOUND TWO GLASS 1-PINT RECEPTICLES.  EACH HAD A SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  ON THE LABELS OF EACH OF THE GLASS RECEPTICLES WAS THE FOLLOWING INFORATION.  "BENZOIN COUMPOUND, TINCTURE, 77% FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER. IT WARRIVED FROM THE SHIPPER THE FOLLOWING DAY.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET SHOWED THAT THE MATERIAL LISTED HAD A FLALSH POINT OF 50 DEGREES F. THERE WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ-MAT SORT, IN THE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS CABINET, PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 PM ON OCTOBER 21, CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT DRIVER JERRY JOHNSON NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE VALVE ON CARGO TANK NUMBER 196.     JERRY CHECKED THE VALVE, WHICH APPEARED TO BE CRACKED, THEN CALLED IN TO REPORT THE LEAKAGE TO DISPATCH.      SHOP FOREMAN RONNIE DUNCAN CALLED ME AND EXPLAINED THE SITUATION. I DIRECTED HIM TO IMMEDIATELY TAKE A TRACTOR AND EMPTY CARGO TANK TO THE SCENE AND TRANSFER THE MATERIAL.     I THEN RESPONDED TO THE SCENE WITH SAFETY AND SPILL CONTAINMENT EQUIPMENT.      A VACUUM TRAILER WAS ALSO DISPATCHED TO REMOVE THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE GROUND.      EMPLOYEES LEAVING WORK FROM A NEARBY CHEMICAL PLANT ASSISTED IN CONTAINING THE SPILL RUNOFF BY DIKING THE DRAIN DITCH WITH SODA ASH. CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT'S CREW TRANSFERRED THE LOAD TO ANOTHER TANKER. IMMEDIATELY AFTER TRANSFERRING THE LOAD, VACUUMING OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL BEGAN WITH THE VACUUM TANK.  ALL VISIBLE LIQUID WAS VACUUMED FROM THE DITCH AND DIKED AREA.      A PH TEST REVEALED THAT THE SPILLED MATERIAL HAD A PH OF 12.  A SOLUTION OF VINEGAR AND WATER WAS THEN USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL AREA RESULTING IN A REDUCTION OF THE PH TO 10. APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF VINEGAR WAS USED.      WE QUIT THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION AT 12:30 AM AND RESUMED THE EFFORT AT 8:00 AM THE FOLLOWING MORNING.      THE PH WAS CHECKED AGAIN BEFORE STARTING AND FOUND TO BET 10. 35 GALLONS MORE VINEGAR WAS THEN USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL AREA IN AN EFFORT TO LOWER THE PH FURTHER. THE PH WAS BROUGHT DOWN TO 9 AND EXCAVATION OF THE MATERIAL BEGAN.    THE LEAKING TRAILER HAD TO BE MOVED APPROXIMATELY 40 FEET IN ORDER FOR THE MATERIAL TO BE PUMPED INTO THE EMPTY TANK. THIS ENLARGED THE SPILL AREA CAUSING MUCH MORE SOIL TO BECOME CONTAMINATED AND REQUIRING REMOVAL.  ALL VISIBLE SOIL WAS REMOVED WITH AN EXCAVATOR AND LOADED ONTO END DUMP EQUIPMENT OPERATED BY CLEAN-UP. AFTER EXCAVATING THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, ED THOMPSON, AN INSPECTOR WITH THE ARKANSAS POLLUTION CONTROL AND ECOLOGY DEPARTMENT, CHECKED AND APPROVED THE SITE WAS READY FOR BACKFILL.  THE SITE WAS FILLED, SEEDED AND FERTILIZED.         A FULL SCAN TCLP, RCI AND PAINT FILTER ANALYSIS WERE PERFORMED ON THE EXCAVATED MATERIAL WHICH VERIFIED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS NON-HAZARDOUS.     THE MATERIAL WAS THEN ACCEPTED BY AND TRANSPORTED TO WASTE MANAGEMENT'S MAGNOLIA LANDFILL IN MONROE, LOUISIANA.     CARGO TANK #196 WAS CHECKED. THE EMERGENCY VALVE WAS ALLOWING MATERIAL AROUND ITS SEAT DUE TO A BROKEN SEALING RING. THE MATERIAL WAS THEN LEAKING FROM THE OUTERMOST VALVE DUE TO THE CORROSIVE ACTION OF THE "GREEN LIQUOR" WHICH WAS BEING TRANSPORTED.     THE EMERGENCY VALVE WAS REPAIRED AND THE OUTER VALVE REPLACED. AFTER REPAIR THE TANK WAS TESTED AND PLACED BACK IN SERVICE.OTHER VALVES OF THE SAME TYPE WERE CHECKED. ONE OTHER ALUMINUM VALVE WAS FOUND AND REPLACED WITH ONE MADE FROM STEEL.

HE HAD JEFREY FIELD FROM CONSIGNEE (SCHUMACHER) PICK UP MATERIAL AND CLEAN UP AREA. SCHUMACHER DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL. WE NEVER OPENED THE CRATE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment; Rollover Accident
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT PIHO 25 TRAIN HAD DERAILED AT RIVER SIDE , TX, AND ACFX 81197 HAD OVERTURNED.  SSA/HM REEDER RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT TWO SAFETY BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WERE NOT IN POSITION. THIS ALLOWED OIL TO LEAK FROM AROUND THE SEAL.  BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED WHICH SLOWED THE LEAK AND CAR WAS UPRIGHTED.  ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE THEN REPOSITIONED AND TIGHTENED.  CAR WAS SET OUT TO TRANSFER 911/09/92). CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) R. CERDA WAS CONDUCTING ROUTINE INSPECTION WHEN HE NOTED AN ODOR COMING FROM ONE OF THE TANK CARS. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT CAR DUPX 9655 WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  CLOSER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID INTAKE VALVE WAS MISSING THE BLIND FLANGE COVERING AND THAT THE AIR INTAKE VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN WITH THE PLUG HANGING ON THE SAFETY CHAIN TO THE SIDE OF THE VALVE.  ALL COMPONENTS WERE AVAILABLE TO PROPERLY SECURE CAR. FITINGS WERE PROPERLY CLOSED WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE OF VAPOR. SSA/HM  T.H. SMITH NOTIFIED CHEMTREC OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: JIM WALLACE, ONE OF OUR DRIVERS WAS ON HIS WAY TO MAKING A HYOCHLORITE DELIVERY TO HUKILL CHEMICAL CO. IN BEDFORD, OHIO AND AFTER SCALING AT CARR BROS., HE BEGAN TO CROSS RT. 8 AND PROCEED DOWN KRICK ROAD. HE GLANCED IN THE REAR VIEW MIRROR AND OBSERVED BLEACH HITTING THE ROAD. HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE TRACTOR, WENT TO THE REAR OF THE TANKER TO INVESTIGATE AND DISCOVERED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BLOWN AND BLEACH WAS COMING THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF LINE THAT RUNS DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANKER FROM THE RUPTURE DISC. JIM IMMEDIATELY CALLED BACK TO JONES CHEMICALS AND OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS SENT OUT TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN, WE HAVE ADDED A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AS A BACKUP TO THE RUPTURE DISC.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE AND STAIN. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS ELEVEN {11} GLASS AND PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE FOUND INSIDE. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED WHERE THE MATERIAL WAS INDICATED TO BE TRANSFORMER OIL BELIEVED TO BE NON-HAZARDOUS. A SECOND CALL WAS MADE AND INDICATED THE MATERIAL TO CONTAIN 135 PPM OF PCB'S. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELLING TO INDICATE THE INNER CONTENTS WERE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTACTED AT 919/840-5506 WHERE SPECIAL AGENT ROBERT ROULAND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SHIPMENT. THE STATE EPA WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS NORTH BOUND ON COUNTY ROAD 71, HE WAS ABOUT TO MAKE A LEFT HAND TURN ONTO COUNTY ROAD 32. A DEER RAN ACROSS THE ROAD, HE TRIED TO AVOID THE DEER AND LOST CONTROL, THE LOAD SHIFTED FROM THE SUDDEN TURN AND THE VEHICLE ROLLED AND LANDED IN THE DITCH. THE VEHICLE HAD CAUGHT ON FIRE IMMEDIATELY AND BURNED TO THE GROUND WITH PERIODIC EXPLOSIONS. THE DRIVER ESCAPED WITH ONLY MINOR INJURIES. FIRE/POLICE DEPARTMENTS, MINNESOTA D.O.T. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALISTS, MISSISSIPPI TRANSPORT, INC. PERSONAL, ETC., WERE ON THE SCENE. A TELEPHONE  REPORT WAS MADE AT 0830 TO THE "MATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER." OFFICER STILLWAGON TOOK THE INCOMING REPORT, THE REPORT NUMBER ID #139278. ACTIONS TAKEN HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTIONS TO MAKE SOUND JUDGEMENTS AS TO WHAT THEY SHOULD NOT DO WHEN DEER ARE PRESENT ON THE ROADWAY.
